Temporary traffic changes around the University of Wollongong and TAFE NSW will be in place from Monday 27 February 2023 for approximately six weeks, to minimise congestion for the start of the university year. 


The temporary traffic changes are as follows:

  • M1 southbound traffic exiting at University Avenue will be diverted left, to make a U-turn at the eastern roundabout, between 7.45am and 9.15am on weekdays. 
  • Traffic at Irvine Street will be diverted to the University Western Access route via Murphys Avenue and Robsons Road during peak periods.  
  • Motorists accessing the M1 northbound ramp (towards Sydney) at Northfields Avenue during peak periods will be diverted via Murphys Avenue and Robsons Road.  

Bus access from University Avenue into Irvine Street will not be affected during diversions and outside peak periods traffic will continue to access the University via Irvine Street and Northfields Avenue.

Continuous closure northbound from 1130pm Sat 25 Feb to 7am Sun 5 Mar

Resident access will be maintained.

Motorists are advised of changed traffic conditions on the Pacific Motorway between Mailmans Track and Archville Station roads, Bonville for vegetation management and essential maintenance work to be carried out.

Work will be carried out 24 hours a day from 5.00am Monday 13 March to 5.00pm Friday 17 March.

 A temporary detour via Pine Creek Way (former Pacific Highway) will be in place while work is carried out on the north and southbound carriageways.

  •  Northbound motorists will exit the motorway at the Mailmans Track Road off ramp, travel 5.5km on Pine Creek Way and re-enter the motorway via the Archville Station Road on ramp
  •   Southbound motorists will exit the motorway at the Archville Station Road off ramp, travel 5.5 km on Pine Creek Way and re-enter the motorway via the Mailmans Track Road on ramp.

Oversize and overmass vehicles will be managed under traffic control with an escort through the work site for vehicles exceeding 4.6 metres in width and 30 metres in length.

Motorists are advised to drive to the conditions and follow the directions of signs and traffic control.
